For audit purposes, we need the following checks: that the request has been received, that the information matches, that the money has been booked against the correct matter, and the time stamps to show the sequence of events before money lands in the account. That helps demonstrate compliance with regulatory timelines.

ServiceNow can capture many of the fields we need: matter details, expected amount, dates, and other fields. Ideally many of these fields will be populated automatically from the matter system so we reduce manual entry and avoid errors.

We can create states and sub-states in ServiceNow — for example, pending, pending transfer, waiting for completion — and tie workflows to those states. That allows automation of next steps and scheduled actions and supports reporting. There are also capabilities for SLAs and alerts which can be leveraged to flag when expected dates are breached.

We should capture expected settlement dates on the form, especially for settlements. If the request relates to a settlement, the requester should indicate that. That can prompt additional fields, such as the expected settlement date, so the team can monitor timelines and prioritise work.

We also have statutory deposit and regulatory obligations: certain trust account balances must be maintained, and transfers sometimes have minimum processing times — for example, a 24-hour rule for depositing funds before they’re available. Capturing settlement dates and ensuring sufficient lead time is important for liquidity and compliance.

ServiceNow can also hold options for the requester to select a reason for funds (e.g., prepayment of legal fees, settlement) and pop up required additional fields accordingly. Structured reasons reduce free-text entries and help with reporting.

We need the ability to add free-text notes and root causes when the expected amount differs, because sometimes a change in funds requires explanation (e.g., a payer changed source). Work notes should capture these communications rather than sending separate emails. That creates a full chain in ServiceNow.

Regarding dashboards and reporting: we need to be able to run reports for upcoming settlements (next seven days, past seven days), overdue expected dates, and other metrics. We can schedule reports, export them, and distribute as required.

Prioritisation is important. For example, settlements due today should be at the top of the queue and assigned higher priority. The requester should be able to flag priority (e.g., settlement vs. general trust receipt). The dashboard should allow the team to view items in order of priority and expected dates.

Team structure: how many cashiers in each location? In Australia we’re five people including a team leader. You should be able to assign tasks or have auto-routing based on role, skills or rotation. We rotate tasks quarterly, but the system should allow assignment to a specific person and view who’s working on which items. We have skills and some people handle specific types of transactions, so role-based routing makes sense.

Payment types: incoming payments are generally electronic into the bank account. We rarely receive cheques for client funds; cheques are mostly office expenses or outgoing funds. The incoming payment path is usually electronic transfers into trust ledgers.

Workflow summary: requests come in, checklists are completed, money arrives, we check allocation and supporting evidence, and notifications can be sent back to the requester. When the matter is closed, or when money is paid out, a ServiceNow task can reflect those actions. For interest accounts and other banking actions, ServiceNow can capture the state and details even if the actual bank change is done outside the system.

Interest accounts: when money is held for a significant period (e.g., property settlements that can take months), clients may want interest to be earned. We ask on the request whether the client wants interest. If yes, we open a specific interest account and move funds into it. These are virtual accounts on our system — the banking platform has cut-off times (e.g., 4:00pm) so some actions happen the next business day. Opening some bank accounts (e.g., CMA accounts) requires bank-specific forms and signatures; we prepare the documentation and the bank executes the account opening, so ServiceNow should capture the status of that external approval process.

Approvals: some actions require approvals outside the cashiering team — for example, partner sign-off for opening client accounts or bank processes. ServiceNow should capture the approval workflow and the resulting state even if the execution is external. Two signatures may be required for some banking instructions; we need a record of that.

Peer checks and reconciliation: at the end of the day we do peer review and reconcile bank statements to ensure postings are correct. We would like ServiceNow to support a reviewed/closed status and to generate reports that show items reviewed and completed.

Operational considerations: we can iterate the ServiceNow form and workflow as we move forward. Initially, use a dashboard as your daily worklist, then evolve routing and automation based on workload and skill sets. The system should support public queues and personal assignments, and allow managers to reassign tasks based on daily priorities.

In summary, the key needs are:
- A ServiceNow form to capture expected receipts with structured fields (matter, amount, expected date, reason, interest preference).
- A checklist and time-stamped audit trail, exportable to PDF for auditors.
- Integration with Intact (client codes, matter details) to reduce manual entry.
- Dashboards and reports for prioritisation (settlements, due dates, breaches).
- Workflow states and sub-states to reflect processing stages.
- Ability to capture external approvals and bank actions, plus free-text work notes for exceptions.
- Role-based routing and assignment, with capacity to rotate tasks and view team workload.

That covers the overall path: request coming in, work performed with checklists, supporting evidence recorded, notifications back to requesters, and final reconciliation and peer review.

